        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-01-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-01-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="66"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d66">
                <head>66. Oral Reply From the Soviet Ambassador (<persName corresp="#p_DAF1"
                        type="from">Dobrynin</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3" type="to">Rusk</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d66fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Subject File, Nuclear Testing—<gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                            >USSR</gloss>, Vol. I, Box 31. Confidential; <gloss target="#t_Limdis1"
                            >Limdis</gloss>. A copy is also reproduced in <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGT1">Seaborg</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi>,
                        Vol. 10, p. 101.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-01-25">January 25, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>An underground nuclear explosion was indeed carried out in the Soviet Union.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d66fn2">Regarding this Soviet test, see <ref target="#d62"
                            >Document 62</ref>.</note> This explosion was carried out deep down
                    underground. The quantity of radioactive debris that leaked into the atmosphere
                    was, however, so insignificant that a possibility of its fallout outside the
                    territorial limits of the Soviet Union should be excluded. Thus, the underground
                    explosion that was carried out does not affect the provisions of the Treaty
                    Banning Nuclear Weapons Tests in the Atmosphere, in Outer Space and
                    Underwater.</p>
            </div>
